04485nam a22006735i 9781400834273DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20102010nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008342737 a10.1515/97814008342732doi  a(DE-B1597)446822  a(OCoLC)979632405  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aBIO0180002bisacsh1 aHeilman, Samuel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Rebbe :bThe Life and Afterlife of Menachem Mendel Schneerson /cSamuel Heilman, Menachem Friedman.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b28 halftones.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tThe Rebbes of ChaBaD -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Farbrengen -- tChapter 2. Death and Resurrection -- tChapter 3. Coming of Age in a Time of Transition -- tChapter 4. Entering the Court of Lubavitch -- tChapter 5. From Survival to Uforatzto -- tChapter 6. On a Mission from the Rebbe in Life -- tChapter 7. From Resurrection to Death -- tChapter 8. On a Mission from the Rebbe in His Afterlife -- tGlossary of Hasidic and Lubavitcher Terms -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the 1950s until his death in 1994, Menachem Mendel Schneerson--revered by his followers worldwide simply as the Rebbe--built the Lubavitcher movement from a relatively small sect within Hasidic Judaism into the powerful force in Jewish life that it is today. Swept away by his expectation that the Messiah was coming, he came to believe that he could deny death and change history. Samuel Heilman and Menachem Friedman paint an unforgettable portrait of Schneerson, showing how he reinvented himself from an aspiring French-trained electrical engineer into a charismatic leader who believed that he and his Lubavitcher Hasidic emissaries could transform the world. They reveal how his messianic convictions ripened and how he attempted to bring the ancient idea of a day of redemption onto the modern world's agenda. Heilman and Friedman also trace what happened after the Rebbe's death, by which time many of his followers had come to think of him as the Messiah himself. The Rebbe tracks Schneerson's remarkable life from his birth in Russia, to his student days in Berlin and Paris, to his rise to global renown in New York, where he developed and preached his powerful spiritual message from the group's gothic mansion in Crown Heights, Brooklyn. This compelling book demonstrates how Schneerson's embrace of traditionalism and American-style modernity made him uniquely suited to his messianic mission.Some images inside the book are unavailable due to digital copyright restrictions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aHabad. 0aHasidimxBiographyxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aHasidimzNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 0aRabbisxBiographyxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aRabbiszNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Religious.2bisacsh1 aFriedman, Menachem, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400834273zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400834273423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400834273.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK